_0013.text: 1.a Discussing with team the local places to grab a coffee.

_0014.text: 1.b Deciding to go to Starbucks and work on design reports.

_0015.text: 1.c Hoping to find a close parking spot.

_0016.text: 1.d Hoping Starbucks is not overly crowded and will have avail-able seating.

_0017.text: 1.e Consider-ing alternative places just in case..

_0018.text: 2.a Notice that there are a couple of people in line.

_0020.text: 2.c Enjoy the aroma of roasted coffee and mixed sweet, robust smells.

_0021.text: 2.d The light-ing is pleasant, not overly bright and not too dim.

_0022.text: 2.e The music seems ethnic, extended vocals, soft in style, volume too load and but my taste.

_0023.text: 2.f The room climate seems intentionally cold.

_0024.text: 3.a The wait-ing line occu-pies the main traffic way.

_0025.text: 3.b The menus across the counter are hard to read while in line.

_0026.text: 3.c The line moves slow, people who just ordered are still in the same area. Becomes crowded.

_0027.text: 3.d The order-ing process seems too slow. Inconsis-tent structure of service.

_0028.text: 4.a The Barista acknowledges me with a smile.

_0029.text: 4.b I can see the menu bet-ter now, but I feel rushed to order a drink.

_0030.text: 4.c I feel forced to make a quick beverage se-lection. I play it safe by having what I always get.

_0031.text: 4.d The baris-ta confirms my selection and asks my name to write on the cup.

_0032.text: 4.e He writes down my name and some code on the cup and hands it off to another barista who will make it when he is finished with other orders.

_0033.text: 5.a The barista tells me the total and I pay with my credit card. He asks me if I want my receipt, I decline.

_0034.text: 5.b My inter-action ends with him say-ing thank you. He doesnt use my name.

_0035.text: 5.c Now I move to the left of where i paid. Once again I feel crowded and out of place. People are walking by me. There isnt a designated waiting ,sitting area.

_0036.text: 5.d As I stand, the drinker maker shouts finished orders and places them on a drink stand. He screams Grande Chai.

_0037.text: 5.e Confu-sion. Is this my drink? Why did he not call out my name or name and drink? I pick up the drink and see that it has Eric writ-ten on it.

_0038.text: 6.a Grab my drink and look for a place to sit.

_0039.text: 6.b I need, most im-portantly, an outlet and a workspace.

_0040.text: 6.c I notice that there are only a few locations in the seating ar-eas that have outlets. This is discouraging.

_0041.text: 6.d Most places are occupied. No outlets are available.

_0042.text: 6.e The work-spaces seem small and impractical. Most are just have a small round wooden table with two wooden chairs.

_0043.text: 6.f I find an empty reclined cushioned armchair. Next to it is a small wooden table shared by another person sitting in the other arm chair.

_0044.text: 6.g The chair is comfortable and I continue to sit in it.

_0045.text: 7.a The cub is hot, steaming, but withstand-ing in my hand.

_0047.text: 7.c First sip is too hot, but flavorful. Im happy with the taste and my choice.

_0049.text: 8.a I place my drink on the table next me and place my bag on the floor.

_0050.text: 8.f I enjoy the free wireless and the unlim-ited use. The signal strength is adequate.

_0051.text: 8.b I remove my computer and accesso-ries and now am shifting my coffee to find room for all of my things on this little cof-fee table.

_0052.text: 8.g The music is really both-ering me. I put my head-phones on and play my mp3 songs.

_0053.text: 8.c The table is too low to work from there, so I place my laptop in my lap. My drink remains on the table, my bag on the floor.

_0054.text: 8.h The bat-tery use on my computer is a concern now. I will begin looking for another table to work at.

_0055.text: 8.d Im feel-ing crowded. I have no room to use my wire-less mouse. I now use the surface of the arm chair as my mouse pad. Not very effective.

_0056.text: 8.i The air conditioning seems inten-tion. Its cold outside and cold inside. I slip my jacket on.

_0057.text: 8.e The crowd talking doesnt bother me after awhile, but the music is way too loud and beginning to become a distraction.

_0058.text: 8.j I continually finding myself people watch-ing while I work. There are interesting people here, so Im not too bothered. I never like feel-ing alone. any

_0059.text: 9.a The barista walks by me and makes an announce-ment to the store that it will be closing shorty -10 pm.

_0060.text: 9.b I would like to continue to work. I feel 10pm closing time is much too early, especially in a college town.

_0061.text: 9.c I stand up and walk around until I find a hidden trash can to throw my cup into.

_0062.text: 10.a I pack my things up and head out the door.

_0063.text: 10.b The re-maining staff tell me to have a good night.

_0064.text: 11.a I head to my car and wish that I could have stayed longer to work. I know that once I get home, I will be in the wrong mind state to continue working.

_0065.text: 11.b The cof-fee was very good, but I was disap-pointed in the environment. Distracting music, small workspace, lack of power outlets.

_0140.text: Furniture not ideal for computer work
